There has been a substantial decline in mortality in Australia during the 20th 
century, with a major improvement in life expectancy. There has been a broad 
"health transition", from a pattern of high mortality from infectious diseases 
to one of lower overall mortality from non-communicable diseases and injury. 
From 1951, trends in death rates from major causes were evident, with the rise 
and partial fall of two epidemics (coronary heart disease and stroke, and lung 
cancer). This overall picture masks significant inequalities in health for 
