The National Kidney Foundation has identified the use arteriovenous grafts (AVG) 
and the interventions required to maintain their patency as two major causes of 
increased expenditure in the management of hemodialysis access in end-stage 
renal disease patients. They have issued an appeal for the increased use of 
native arteriovenous fistulae (AVF). Although the radialcephalic AVF is 
considered to be the procedure of choice for these patients, other veins should 
be sought after to maintain an all-autogenous AVF policy. We examined our 
experience of using arm veins that were transposed to the brachial artery. Over 
the last 2.5 years, 109 brachiocephalic AVF (BCAVF) and 63 brachiobasilic AVF 
(BBAVF) were placed in 163 patients with chronic renal failure. In each group, 
