Surgical treatment of morbid obesity: role of the gastroenterologist.

Greve JW(1).

Author information:
(1)Dept. of Surgery, University Hospital Maastricht, P. O. Box 5800, 6202 AZ 
Maastricht, The Netherlands. jgre@shee.azm.nl

AIM: Obesity is an increasing medical problem with associated disorders such as 
type 2 diabetes mellitus, cardiovascular disorders and many others. The chance 
to develop co-morbidity is related to the body mass index (BMI) (weight in kg 
divided by height in metres2) and increases exponentially when the BMI is above 
40 (morbid obesity). Permanently effective treatment of morbid obesity is 
necessary to prevent the development of co-morbidities and to improve the life 
